{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503073"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:54:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:54:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1928"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1928"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.37,0.11,0.21,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1928"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77095"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1928"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1928"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62601"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"960"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3169"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26542"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77095","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77095"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a 24-hour history of crampy, generalised abdominal pain which has localised to the right side and become constant. She feels nauseated but has not vomited. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her last menstrual period was two weeks ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. There is localised tenderness in the right iliac fossa without guarding or rebound. A plain abdominal radiograph is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the radiological findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Faecolith","Dermoid cyst","Bladder calculus","Staghorn calculus","Uterine fibroid"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe radiograph shows tooth-like calcifications in the pelvis. While the clinical presentation might suggest acute appendicitis, the radiological findings are characteristic of a \u003Cstrong\u003Edermoid cyst\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as a mature cystic teratoma. These benign ovarian tumours contain well-differentiated tissues derived from all three germ cell layers, commonly including teeth, hair, and sebaceous material. They are the most common ovarian neoplasm in women of reproductive age and are often found incidentally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Efaecolith\u003C/strong\u003E typically appears as a rounded or oval opacity, often with concentric laminations. While they can occur in the appendix (appendicolith), they do not show the distinct tooth-like appearance seen in this image.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBladder calculi\u003C/strong\u003E generally appear as rounded or oval radiopaque shadows that may change position with patient movement. They are typically smooth-edged rather than showing the irregular, tooth-like appearance seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStaghorn calculi\u003C/strong\u003E form a branching pattern within the renal collecting system and would be visible in the renal area, not in the pelvis. They typically conform to the shape of the collecting system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUterine fibroids\u003C/strong\u003E can calcify, but this typically occurs in post-menopausal women. When calcified, they appear as popcorn-like calcifications rather than distinct tooth-like structures.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dermoid cysts (mature cystic teratomas) characteristically contain well-differentiated tissues including teeth, hair, and sebaceous material visible on imaging.","Dermoid cysts are the most common ovarian neoplasm in women of reproductive age.","The presence of tooth-like calcifications on plain radiograph in a woman of reproductive age strongly suggests dermoid cyst."],"references":["Outwater EK, Siegelman ES, Hunt JL. Ovarian Teratomas: Tumor Types and Imaging Characteristics. Radiographics. 2001;21(2). Available at: https://doi.org/10.1148/radiographics.21.2.g01mr09475"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62601"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1928"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20396"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20396"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/lJHBZokw0ND4hbN3ENvdNiKbCLLPDa.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/lJHBZokw0ND4hbN3ENvdNiKbCLLPDa.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":696,"height":543}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62601"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T09:02:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T09:02:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1928"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77095"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"descriptio